<definition xml:id="definition-linear_combination">
    <title>Linear Combination</title>
    <statement>
        <p>
            If  <m> a </m>  and <m> b </m> are integers, then an integer <m> c </m> is a <term>linear combination</term> of <m> a </m>  and <m> b </m> if there exist integers <m> x </m> and <m> y </m> such that <m>c = ax + by</m>.
        </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>

<p>
  We now prove one of the fundamental tools of number theory, the division algorithm.  We will use the division algorithm to prove some of the most important results in number theory, including the Euclidean Algorithm and the Fundamental Theorem of Arithmetic. 
</p>

<proposition xml:id="proposition-divisibility_of_linear_combination">
  <title>Divisibility and linear combinations</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      If <m>a,b,c\in \Z</m> where <m>c\mid a</m> and <m>c\mid b</m>, then <m>c\mid ax+by</m>.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <proof>
    <p>
      Try a direct proof.  Let the definitions structure your proof.  You may find  <xref ref="definition-divisibility"/> and <xref ref="definition-commutative_ring"/>useful.
    </p>
  </proof>
</proposition>


